the air was heavy with pine and juniper. the wind dancing through their soft needles. 

the forest floor holds quiet evidence of time long past. in sun puddles and shadows. 

among the faces of stone, the lichens and moss grow together as one. a shared existence. 

silhouetted leaves. the warmth of dappled sunlight. and a loving hand to hold. 

walking in beauty. a rhythmic breath, a singular heartbeat. a part of it all.

this is home.
deep in their roots, all flowers keep the light. – theodore roethke 🌙🥀🕯️

painful magnetic
pull to walk deeper
and deeper into
their beauty. they
keep me
continuously

honoring the transformative growth and beauty that can be born only from the darkness and the warm, gentle reawakening of the light on this winter solstice threshold. 🌙🥀❄️

the sun that will, eventually call all the medicine held in the earth up to the sky in tendrils of green, in unfurling wildness and beauty.

there are many tales that can be told about the darkness and it's beauty, it's vital role.

and at this time i like to thank those ones who work so well in the rich fertile places.

ask the seed of the magic that is held in the darkness and they will show you a story of growth and transformation.

ask the roots of the magic they know of deep within the black and they will tell you a mineral rich story of nourishment, strength and grounding.

ask the mycelium of what they know of darkness and they will show you a story of connection and reciprocity.

ask the worm what they feel in that blackness and they will tell you about alchemy, of the life that springs from
death.

may you find, when listening in the dark, those things within, for they are there, held in psyche, heart and bone.

the brave and caring alchemist, the wild reciprocity, the strength and grounding, the growth and beauty.

– spellbinding words by the ever-magical 
@brigitannamcneill

what do the stones have to say
about slowing down,
about gracefully settling into
who you truly are?

about loving the world
just as it is, and offering 
a resting place 
a source of peace 
for anyone in need 

about being still enough 
to become a quiet home
for life to unfold 
in mosses, in lichens
in darkness, in roots

in the heat of the sun
and the silver cool
of the moon

listen — the stones whisper,
here is our secret:
if you are still enough 
and let yourself really rest 

over time
you will become
the whole forest

to begin with, the sweet grass | mary oliver

will the hungry ox stand in the field and not eat of the sweet grass? will the owl bite off its own wings? will the lark forget to lift its body in the air or forget to sing? will the rivers run upstream?  behold, i say—behold the reliability and the finery and the teachings of this gritty earth gift.  eat bread and understand comfort. drink water, and understand delight. visit the garden where the scarlet trumpets are opening their bodies for the hummingbirds who are drinking the sweetness, who are thrillingly gluttonous.  for one thing leads to another. soon you will notice how stones shine underfoot. eventually tides will be the only calendar you believe in.  and someone’s face, whom you love, will be as a star both intimate and ultimate, and you will be both heart-shaken and respectful.  and you will hear the air itself, like a beloved, whisper: oh, let me, for a while longer, enter the two beautiful bodies of your lungs.  the witchery of living is my whole conversation with you, my darlings. all i can tell you is what i know.  look, and look again. this world is not just a little thrill for the eyes.  it’s more than bones.
it’s more than the delicate wrist with its personal pulse.
it’s more than the beating of the single heart.
it’s praising.
it’s giving until the giving feels like receiving. you have a life—just imagine that! you have this day, and maybe another, and maybe still another.  let me ask you this. do you also think that beauty exists for some fabulous reason?  and, if you have not been enchanted by this 
adventure— your life— what would do for you?

and what do i risk to tell you this, which is all i know? love yourself. then forget it. then, love the world.

walking in beauty — 🌼

may, and among the miles of leafing, blossoms storm out of the darkness— windflowers and moccasin flowers. the bees dive into them and i too, to gather their spiritual honey. mute and meek, yet theirs is the deepest certainty that this existence too— this sense of well-being, the flourishing of the physical body—rides near the hub of the miracle that everything is a part of, is as good as a poem or a prayer, can also make luminous any dark place on earth.

– mary oliver | may

late spring | mary oliver 🌸

finally the world is beginning
to change, its fever mounting,
its leaves unfolding.

and the mockingbirds find
ample reason and breath to fashion
new songs. they do. you can
count on it.

as for lovers, they are discovering,
new ways to love. listen, their windows are open.
you can hear them laughing.

without spring who knows what would happen. 
a lot of nothing, i suppose.
the leaves are all in motion now
the way a young boy rows and rows

in his wooden boat, just to get anywhere.
late, late, but now lovely and lovelier. 
and the two of us together — a part of it.

mary oliver’s magical ‘late spring’ dedicated to these late mountain bloomers. crab apple blossoms always take me back to my childhood, climbing the apple trees in the wilds of our backyard. memories that immediately put my heart at ease and serve as the most precious reminder to continuously + lovingly reconnect to that untamed part of myself. the scraped limbs, grass-stained knees, tangled hair, unbridled messiness + joy of simply being. fully embodied. it’s beautiful how flowers can energetically transport us just as they have the ability to hold us and provide deep healing throughout the many chapters of our lives. both in the the shedding + the becoming. 

claiming the magic in this tender spiritual nudge i received from sitting with the crab apple today and sending a whole pocketful of it’s medicine to the hearts who need it most — may you forever find the courage to live boldly + with great intention. to follow the threads of joy meant only for you. to blossom into the fullest authentic expression of your beautiful being.

🌙🌸🍯

once in awhile in a big blue moon there comes a night like this…

joni mitchell’s ever-poetic ‘night ride home’ echoed through my mind while soaking in the rare magic of this evening’s blue supermoon in pisces. full moons often usher in the most beautiful sense of release. the phase of the lunar cycle that inspires us to let go of anything that feels too heavy to carry — making room for only joy and ease. 

with two full moons bookending the month of august, i can’t help but feel a potent sense of change in the air. a closing of a chapter. from waxing to waning. bloom to seed. late summer into early autumn. 

my blue moon wish is that this lunation leaves us all feeling a little bit lighter as we approach a new month and nearing shift in season. with hearts wide open to the wonder and awe ever-present in our days. as if each divine moment of beauty that touches our lives was written in the stars just for us. with a quiet knowing that they always have been — and will forever continue to be as we journey on.

are promising.

and necessary
decay. the edge
of triumph 
before the deep 
rest.

on september twenty-ninth, in a lakeside forest clearing beneath the pine trees and shimmering aspens, he asked for my hand + my heart forever. 

the most majestic bald eagle, white-tailed deer, and bull moose sightings blessed the day. spirit messengers appearing in sacred, serendipitous moments that felt divinely sent.

the harvest moon a bright, beaming companion on the drive home. a shining reminder of the fullness of our love. 

there is no sweeter feeling than when the world around you comes together in harmonious support of your deepest dreams. 

and on this day, every quiet heart wish i’ve ever held came true. it’s always been him.

look, the trees are turning their own bodies into pillars

of light, are giving off the rich fragrance of cinnamon and fulfillment,

the long tapers of cattails are bursting and floating away over the blue shoulders

of the ponds, and every pond, no matter what its name is, is

nameless now. every year everything i have ever learned

in my lifetime leads back to this: the fires and the black river of loss whose other side

is salvation, whose meaning none of us will ever know. to live in this world

you must be able to do three things: to love what is mortal; to hold it

against your bones knowing your own life depends on it; and, when the time comes to let it go, to let it go.

mary oliver | in blackwater woods

when i am among the trees, especially the willows and the honey locust, equally the beech, the oaks and the pines, they give off such hints of gladness. i would almost say that they save me, and daily.

i am so distant from the hope of myself, in which i have goodness, and discernment, and never hurry through the world but walk slowly, and bow often.

around me the trees stir in their leaves and call out, “stay awhile.” the light flows from their branches.

and they call again, “it’s simple,” they say, “and you too have come into the world to do this, to go easy, to be filled with light, and to shine.”

mary oliver | when i am among the trees
